TY  - JOUR
T1  - How Governments Matter to New Industry Creation
AU  - Spencer, Jennifer W.
AU  - Murtha, Thomas P.
AU  - Lenway, Stefanie Ann
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387889
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.16387889
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 321
EP  - 337
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We articulate opportunities and challenges for governments and innovating firms operating within countries that display four types of national political institutional structures. We argue that corporatist and associational institutional structures influence governments' capabilities to support diffusion- and mission-oriented technology policies and firms' tendencies to engage in bricolage or breakthrough approaches to technological entrepreneurship. We then show how the relative strength of state institutions can amplify or compromise governments' policies and firms' innovation strategies.
AB  - We articulate opportunities and challenges for governments and innovating firms operating within countries that display four types of national political institutional structures. We argue that corporatist and associational institutional structures influence governments' capabilities to support diffusion- and mission-oriented technology policies and firms' tendencies to engage in bricolage or breakthrough approaches to technological entrepreneurship. We then show how the relative strength of state institutions can amplify or compromise governments' policies and firms' innovation strategies.
