TY  - JOUR
T1  - Government's Dilemma: The Role of Government in Imitation and Innovation
AU  - Mahmood, Ishtiaq P.
AU  - Rufin, Carlos
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387891
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.16387891
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 338
EP  - 360
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We consider the role of government in the process of technological development, showing that the role of government regarding technological development varies over the development process. When a country is far from the technological frontier, the government can spur economic development through the centralization of economic and political control, but as the economy approaches the technological frontier, government's role must change considerably, political and economic freedom being necessary. In addition, domestic business groups can act as substitutes for governmental intervention, and multinational corporations can supplement governmental efforts.
AB  - We consider the role of government in the process of technological development, showing that the role of government regarding technological development varies over the development process. When a country is far from the technological frontier, the government can spur economic development through the centralization of economic and political control, but as the economy approaches the technological frontier, government's role must change considerably, political and economic freedom being necessary. In addition, domestic business groups can act as substitutes for governmental intervention, and multinational corporations can supplement governmental efforts.
