T1  - The Attractiveness of Political Markets: Implications for Firm Strategy
AU  - Bonardi, Jean-Philippe
AU  - Hillman, Amy J
AU  - Keim, Gerald D.
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387895
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.16387895
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 397
EP  - 413
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We conceptualize democracies as marketlike processes where demanders and suppliers of various public policies interact. Firms may enter political markets to seek new or to maintain existing policies that affect their current business operations or future opportunities. We contend that a firm's decision to become politically active is influenced, in part, by the attractiveness of the political market, and we outline conditions that make political markets more or less attractive for firms to compete in to advance their interests.
AB  - We conceptualize democracies as marketlike processes where demanders and suppliers of various public policies interact. Firms may enter political markets to seek new or to maintain existing policies that affect their current business operations or future opportunities. We contend that a firm's decision to become politically active is influenced, in part, by the attractiveness of the political market, and we outline conditions that make political markets more or less attractive for firms to compete in to advance their interests.
