AU  - Zelner, Bennet A.
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387892
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.16387892
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 361
EP  - 382
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We offer a simple model of policy making, emphasizing socialization and limits on human cognition to explicate mechanisms of change in emergent (as opposed to established) institutions. Emergent institutions are more susceptible to change, and their opponents may use frames or existing reference points to illustrate inconsistency with prevailing notions of legitimacy. Broader institutional structures and specific organizational characteristics moderate pressure for change. This perspective has novel implications for strategy and policy design.
AB  - We offer a simple model of policy making, emphasizing socialization and limits on human cognition to explicate mechanisms of change in emergent (as opposed to established) institutions. Emergent institutions are more susceptible to change, and their opponents may use frames or existing reference points to illustrate inconsistency with prevailing notions of legitimacy. Broader institutional structures and specific organizational characteristics moderate pressure for change. This perspective has novel implications for strategy and policy design.
