TY  - JOUR
T1  - Government Corruption and the Entry Strategies of Multinationals
AU  - Rodriguez, Peter
AU  - Uhlenbruck, Klaus
AU  - Eden, Lorraine
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387894
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2005.16387894
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 383
EP  - 396
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Multinational enterprises (MNEs) often encounter government corruption when operating in host countries; however, in the international management literature, it is typically assumed that government officials pursue national interests rather than their own. We introduce a two-dimensional framework to further the understanding of public sector corruption and identify its implications for MNEs. Using an institutional perspective, we examine how the pervasiveness and arbitrariness of corruption can affect an MNE's organizational legitimacy and strategic decision making. We apply our analysis to the mode of entry decision.
AB  - Multinational enterprises (MNEs) often encounter government corruption when operating in host countries; however, in the international management literature, it is typically assumed that government officials pursue national interests rather than their own. We introduce a two-dimensional framework to further the understanding of public sector corruption and identify its implications for MNEs. Using an institutional perspective, we examine how the pervasiveness and arbitrariness of corruption can affect an MNE's organizational legitimacy and strategic decision making. We apply our analysis to the mode of entry decision.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2005.16387894
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2005.16387894
Y2  - 2026/04/24
